:::summary
Abstract algebra is the branch of mathematics that studies algebraic structures — groups, rings, fields, and vector spaces — by identifying the abstract properties and axioms they share, rather than working with specific numbers or equations. It is a cornerstone of modern mathematics, underlying number theory, geometry, cryptography, and much of theoretical physics.
